🛡️ Stay Safe Online A College Student's Cybersecurity Checklist — India Edition

📋 Your Personal Safety Checklist

🔐 Account & Password Security

-Use strong, unique passwords for every account — Mix uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols. Never reuse the same password across platforms. Use a free password manager like Bitwarden or 1Password to keep track. -Enable Two-Factor Authentication (2FA) everywhere — Turn on 2FA on Gmail, Instagram, WhatsApp, and especially banking apps. Even if someone steals your password, they can't get in without your OTP. -Never share OTPs with anyone — ever — No bank, no government office, no "customer care agent" will ever ask for your OTP over call or chat. If someone asks, it's a scam. Hang up immediately.

💸 UPI & Financial Safety (Must-Know for Every Student)

-Never scan a QR code to receive money — You only scan to pay. If someone says "scan this to get a refund or prize money," it's a fraud. Receiving money never requires scanning or entering a PIN. -Set a daily UPI transaction limit — Go into your UPI app settings (GPay, PhonePe, Paytm) and set a daily limit. This minimizes damage in case your phone or account is ever compromised. -Double-check UPI IDs before every payment — One wrong character in a UPI ID sends money to a stranger. Always verify the recipient's name that appears before confirming. Don't rush payments.

📱 Device & App Safety

-Never install APK files from WhatsApp or unknown links — Fake KYC apps, fake bank apps, and spyware are commonly spread this way in India. Only install apps from the Google Play Store or Apple App Store. -Keep your phone's OS and apps updated — Updates patch security vulnerabilities. Delaying them leaves your device open to known exploits. Turn on auto-updates so you never miss one. -Avoid using public Wi-Fi for banking or personal logins — Free Wi-Fi at cafés, railway stations, or college canteens can be monitored. If you must use it, enable a VPN (like ProtonVPN — free tier available).

🎭 Identity & Social Media Safety

-Audit your social media privacy settings every semester — Check who can see your phone number, location, and date of birth on Instagram, Facebook, and Snapchat. Strangers don't need that information. -Be cautious of fake job/internship offers on Telegram & WhatsApp — "Work from home, earn ₹5000/day" messages targeting college students are among the most common scams in India right now. If it sounds too easy, it's a trap.

🚨 If Something Goes Wrong — Report It Immediately

📞 Helpline: 1930 National Cybercrime Helpline — Call immediately if you've lost money online. The faster you report, the higher the chance of recovery.

🌐 Portal: cybercrime.gov.in File a formal complaint for any cybercrime — financial fraud, cyberbullying, identity theft, morphed images, and more. Available 24/7.
